ng untracked files, but I’m not so sure. Maybe the top-level public class is fine? So much to explore!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering serialization options**\\n\\nI’m thinking about testing serialization and deserialization of the key using `java.security.KeyRep`, but that doesn’t seem to fit. Maybe `java.beans.XMLEncoder`? No, that won’t work either. I wonder if I should check the BouncyCastle upstream tests for JCEDH. It feels a bit like trial and error! There’s a lot to consider, but inspecting those tests might give me some clarity on how to proceed.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_LsdFuh5CvML6wcsMqDv08eve|fc_0f7747aecb615386016a10d9edbfb0819283bc552f8e48eb31", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "rg -n \"JCEDHPublicKey|DHPublicKey|serialization|serialize\" /home/vjovanov/c/forge/forge10/graalvm-reachability-metadata/forge/local_repositories/source_context/org.bouncycastle/bcprov-jdk15on/1.48 -S | head -200", "timeout": 20}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 2415, "output": 1123, "cacheRead": 53248, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 56786, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1779489241174, "responseId": "resp_0f7747aecb615386016a10d9da3f608192886718674ee93803"}}
