[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Analyzing test issues**\n\nI'm thinking about the JCEDHPrivateKey test—it's not active, which might be due to a hardcoded stream issue. It seems all generated tests are untracked and not part of the Git base, so coverage may be outdated. We created a file, but Git shows other files as untracked. I wonder if this is why the workflow only includes tracked files. Maybe the test is not compiling under Java 21 due to certain compatibility issues. ObjectStream's serialVersion might not match either. There’s quite a bit to sort through!\n\n**Examining serialization and coverage**\n\nI'm looking at the JDK 21 BigInteger serialVersionUID, and it seems like it should work. Coverage is probably coming from javaTest, not native. The dynamic access report is likely from a native run, so I’m wondering if the test failure is because \"Attempt 1\" didn’t include our earlier changes. The user's feedback indicates no coverage. We might need to refine the tests further, especially considering how serialization interacts with JCEDHPublicKey and any reflection metadata involved in native image serialization. It's complex!\n\n**Investigating test results**\n\nI’m thinking that the test results might not be from our new file because it wasn't run. It seems the external source is indicating no new tests, possibly based on an old build. I want to consider including the test in the existing BCDHPublicKeyTest, but it might need a one-to-one setup, which we already have. I’m curious if the build tool might be excluding untracked files, but I’m not so sure. Maybe the top-level public class is fine? So much to explore!\n\n**Considering serialization options**\n\nI’m thinking about testing serialization and deserialization of the key using `java.security.KeyRep`, but that doesn’t seem to fit. Maybe `java.beans.XMLEncoder`? No, that won’t work either. I wonder if I should check the BouncyCa