6WbPG7q3LT6iUF4Xc8kbWPn_VCrTdkBdXT_mWHoi58HY_WzRDoTaVAu86C2upVeP-KI75fbjJ-nk44-VtTtJuI-FvhrNVG_BZsFwgRzGWUJdkQ_Rwni9LhT_546t39tFz-FCxxNVoi3g_VP3ifJHfokw6vXDaanCHGS2wiSwjMXhavabdJEeWQpzXcmgcsYPa0oM16GcnprMyk9_-nIi5YZtH1gMvT_HPWx1f0hrqSDN6EfObpbWoBryiWZ0r2dwXAenu6yWs10dMH5lDiM9bhqCIO_EnPaWBZmCuKG2Ksp6AuVdkSPMZylvfkWZLd5twkbtRu7PgWevBmP5ZR6OJlPdC-Pu2f1EzVQjxp52pgzIaFpQnuMxfTn7eHAyPLM2LcktmbXUhvHp9AiFv8F47_piMxcDWETwIR_KdMxOccUOwp4UlY7aojExI2iUe_9rNIR-AaRMcUgn_vwW34IIpWFoJ1-wACklLQzcFeEOqGSrW5FLx-Ze9bp8PXEW7OB1Nye4YpdtTg_COhfieWrz4JwwZHIuBSX1V-07vJHqNL4kVrwy5UNFAdIPNWRAjUDx_XTstemHebDTDcVK-7QN8UkY8mMRtHEqqvuIzi-MS-vdQtqEKyNR3PY60zGvYVvtLz-dqhGsrQxzczY_YaSZluXEpxU9LG9Gm3qiUKDjsHcukBXEXDV_bVOAznv11w9iNXV96qCuFxIAcpqGzYkBXMjuYiXoUUyhpXVcRx6TWGTSvCQErGQmNj_J4PeaPSI8XKS48pgIbI4uRXtTgpLXKdGP9yD8X_Q==\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating Java serialization safety**\\n\\nI'm considering the safety of patching the java.lang.Number SUID with a native variant. Since Number doesn't have fields, I wonder if it's safe. But the object stream from JDK 21 has proper fields for BigInteger. There could be some UID differences due to substitutions, which leads me to think about potential field mismatches during deserialization. However, Java serialization usually handles those without issues. I also wonder if there's a way to bypass BigInteger serialization completely.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating Java serialization**\\n\\nI'm thinking about how this approach avoids mismatches in hardcoded JDK descriptor SUIDs, which sounds quite robust. It's definitely a positive aspect. But does it rely on reflection? Nope, it actually uses the public Java serialization API instead. I find it interesting to see how these mechanisms work together to maintain consistency and effectiveness in serialization. It's a thoughtful way to ensure compatibility in Java's serialization process!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_BvmN3RlKDK27pszNJNEKLRpm|fc_0